    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-10T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-10T03:00:00-05:00" n="231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8694: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-10T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 10, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 10—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>215. Embassy’s 200 [<hi rend="italic">214</hi>], July 10, 1 p.m.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d231fn2">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Naval Attaché and Assistant Military Attaché returned at noon from
                        Wanpinghsien. They report that Japanese troops are no longer on the
                        Peiping-Hankow Railway and that the only Japanese troops visible are some
                        fifty which are stationed some distance on the road to Peiping east of the
                        east gates of Wanpinghsien; that is, the town is between them and the river
                        and Marco Polo Bridge. They are of the opinion that the other Japanese
                        troops have returned to Fengtai. They report that Sung’s men are all west of
                        the river and that Wanpinghsien is garrisoned by Peace Preservation
                        Corps.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Evidence is increasing that the casualties on both sides were considerable
                        and that the Japanese casualties were much larger than officially
                        admitted.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated Nanking, Shanghai, and Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
